label chapter13:

    # [Scene: Municipal Green Atrium | Early Evening — storm]

    scene bg ch11_3be532_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fast, insistent staccato strings under a low synth pulse]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Hail rattles the panes like an impatient drumline; distant chatter, the squeal of a microphone]
    "You came into the Atrium with words to land—metrics and mercy in equal measure. You expected resistance, the thin white glare of legality, maybe Ari's careful smile. You did not expect the thing that makes decisions"
    "suddenly less theoretical: a folder, weighty and plain, thumbed into your palm by Nora without ceremony."
    "The folder is warm from someone's breath. Your fingers find the paper clip that holds the documents together. You do not have to guess what they are; the title on the first page is corporate shorthand"
    "for convenience and consequence. The paper smells faintly of printer toner and the metal tang of rain from the panes. For a sliver of a second the world narrows to the rasp of your pen against"
    "your palm and the steady, too-loud thud of your heart."
    show nora_daz at left:
        zoom 0.7

    nora_daz "We found them in the source dump—old server cascade, someone sloppy. It's everything: contracts, memos, timelines. The names line up."
    show maya_ortega at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ortega "How sure are we—about chain, authenticity?"
    "Nora's jaw tightens. Her hands find yours across the folder as if transferring more than paper."

    nora_daz "Forensic stamp from the firm. Cross-checked with Samir's ledger. It's messy, Maya, but it's not fake."
    "Samir clears his throat, slow and deliberate; the rain gives his words a kind of authority."
    show samir_qureshi at center:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_qureshi "Truth without a road is like a boat without oars. You can shout to the harbor and not get any farther."
    "You feel Luca's presence behind you before you hear his voice—his heat, his impatience, the human pressure that always seems to ask for movement."
    hide nora_daz
    show luca_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    luca_chen "So what are we doing with it? We can drop this tonight. That paper trail will make names burn."
    "Your internal voice tightens into a drumroll: leak and expose, negotiate a safeguard, or fold this back into repair and ritual. Each possibility carries weight that clacks like hail. The atrium's clean light feels thin and brittle against it."

    menu:
        "Flip the folder open and skim the top memo":
            "You flip the top page. Names and dates swim up in black ink—an implementation timeline that maps unsettlingly close to the council's current schedule. Your stomach turns."
        "Tuck the folder into your jacket and wait":
            "You slip the folder beneath your jacket, feeling its bulk against your ribs. The rain becomes a metronome; waiting stretches but also gives you space to think."

    # --- merge ---
    "Narrative continues"
    "You close the folder—because opening it here would be theatrical and dangerous—and the sound of the room rushes back. Council aides pace with tablets; a city lawyer approaches with the soft authority of bureaucracy. Ari stands a few feet away, hands folded, expression an inscrutable schematic of composure and calculation."
    hide maya_ortega
    show ari_nakamura at right:
        zoom 0.7

    ari_nakamura "Maya. I heard there's new information. We can handle this constructively. If there's wrongdoing, I want transparency—if only to cut off the rot."
    "You watch Ari's eyes: amber, precise. Right now his expression is complex—equal parts offer and assessment, a humane calculus folded into career habits."
    hide samir_qureshi
    show maya_ortega at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ortega "Handle how? The neighborhood needs enforceable guarantees, Ari. Not PR."

    ari_nakamura "Agreed. If there are clauses or missteps, we'll audit. I can arrange oversight. We can fix this without spectacle."
    "Luca Chen's hand finds the back of your neck, a quick, private pressure."

    luca_chen "Fixing it without people knowing is fixing it to someone's advantage. If they bury this, they'll keep control."

    ari_nakamura "And if we leak, the city clamps down. Investors panic. Homes get catalogued for relocation out of fear, not necessity. We have to be smarter than anger."

    "The exchange pulls the room taut. You hear a reporter's phone buzzing somewhere near the glass—industry scent in the air, the metallic tang of imminent headlines. Your watch vibrates with a message from an unknown number" "We can go live."
    # [Scene: Walk from the Atrium to the Old Docks | Streets between glass towers and spray]
    hide luca_chen
    hide ari_nakamura
    hide maya_ortega

    scene bg ch11_3be532_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Percussion ratchets up; low strings sustain, brass pinpricks for emphasis]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Wind gusts, distant air traffic, boots slapping wet pavement]
    "You move with the group because standing still here would make them think you still need the city's structures to decide. The storm pushes against you; salt and ozone fill your mouth. Nervous exchanges ricochet—half-voices, held-back accusations, whispers like people trying not to wake something sleeping."
    show nora_daz at left:
        zoom 0.7

    nora_daz "If we leak without a plan, there's a vacuum. The city has lawyers and PR. We have Samir, a few witnesses, and us. That's not an even field."
    show maya_ortega at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ortega "Then what's the plan that doesn't involve silence?"
    show samir_qureshi at center:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_qureshi "A plan is not a list of demands. A plan is an anchor. We need legal teeth—stewardship clauses, relocation protections, enforceable oversight. Without those, a leak is a howl into wind."

    "Luca Chen (frustrated)" "The teeth take time to grow. People need a roof now. If they're hiding collusion, the public has a right to know that every delay was deliberate."
    "You feel the group's tempo: Nora cautious, Samir advising patience, Luca hungry for action, Ari offering contained solutions. Your notebook is in your pocket, the pen like a small keel you keep returning to. You think"
    "of old pilings and new renderings; you think of Samir's ledger and the way the marsh remembers."

    menu:
        "Call the reporter back and test the line":
            "You thumb the screen, listen to the voicemail again. The reporter's voice is crisp, eager—'exclusive' whispered like a pledge. Hanging up feels like stepping back from a spear."
        "Text Ari and ask for immediate oversight meeting":
            "You type a curt message to Ari. The tiny sent pulse returns quickly. It feels like sending out a marker: I'm still in the room."

    # --- merge ---
    "Narrative continues"
    "You arrive at the Old Docks—the hub's patched corrugated face a candle against the storm. Strings of warm bulbs hang inside like a deliberate insistence on light. The door opens and the smell of wet wood"
    "and boiled coffee swallows you; the community's noise is less formal here—voices that carry the weather and the work."
    # [Scene: Old Docks Community Hub | Interior — Night]
    hide nora_daz
    hide maya_ortega
    hide samir_qureshi

    scene bg ch11_3be532_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Tension swells into layered rhythms; a single high violin line threads worry through the air]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The door thuds closed; someone slams a drawer; the radio murmurs a weather alert]
    "Nora sets the folder on the table and slides a sheet toward you: red annotations, legalese highlighted, names circled. The hub's light catches the moisture on each page, turning ink into small islands."
    show nora_daz at left:
        zoom 0.7

    nora_daz "If we push for amendments—stewardship clauses that require local boards, finance set aside for maintenance, explicit anti-displacement provisions—we buy ourselves legal leverage. We force the pilot to be accountable."
    show maya_ortega at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ortega "And the cost?"

    nora_daz "Politically, a lot. Ari's team will resist. Council will call it delay. Developers will point fingers. But enforceable language can be part of any contract."
    show luca_chen at center:
        zoom 0.7

    luca_chen "That's negotiation. That's not exposing the rot. That's letting them keep their hands on the wheel."
    hide nora_daz
    show samir_qureshi at left:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_qureshi "Negotiation is a hand across the tiller, not a surrender. It is also a pace, not a shout. Consider the lives we protect with steady water at the stern."
    "Your phone buzzes. A name you haven't seen in weeks: Ari. You let it go to voicemail; curiosity pricks at the edge of your decision. You play the message—Ari's voice even, practiced but not without something fraying at the edges."
    hide maya_ortega
    show ari_nakamura at right:
        zoom 0.7

    ari_nakamura "Maya. I've seen the documents. I'm calling to propose a line: we open the contract with an independent oversight clause, municipal and community-appointed, with staged funding that releases contingent on measurable stewardship. We can present it to Council as a compromise. It keeps us out of the headlines. Call me."
    "The message ends. In the hush, the hub seems to inhale. Ari's offer is specific; his tone leans conciliatory. It is also a calculated move—either to defuse disclosure or to bind your community into a bureaucratic architecture that may or may not hold."
    hide luca_chen
    show maya_ortega at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ortega "If I sign on to his framework, what do I risk?"

    ari_nakamura "You risk being the face of compromise. You risk giving opponents a talking point. But you also secure enforceable terms faster than litigation, and you avoid a spectacle that leaves people homeless out of fear."

    maya_ortega "And if I don't trust a public framework?"

    ari_nakamura "Then you take your strategy to the public. I won't stop you, but you should know the consequences. Headlines shift budgets; budgets shift bodies."
    "Luca Chen, who has stayed close enough to overhear, snaps back with two quick lines."
    hide samir_qureshi
    show luca_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    luca_chen "Consequences we've been living with. Better to burn the corrupt than let it keep us warm."
    hide ari_nakamura
    show nora_daz at right:
        zoom 0.7

    nora_daz "Or we bind the corrupt with law and make sure the warmth is steady and local."
    "The room turns inward and outward at the same time; you feel the centrifugal force of competing logics. Your skin prickles with urgency. The storm outside presses like a timeline. Your palm rests flat on the folder—proof and poison in one."
    "Samir leans forward, voice low and fierce in a way that has anchored meetings before."
    hide maya_ortega
    show samir_qureshi at center:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_qureshi "Listen. The truth will not protect you if you have nowhere to put it. If you shout, make sure you have shelter ready for the people who will come to your door. If you write, make sure the words are teeth. If you step back, make sure the rituals that keep us together continue to be tended. Each path demands a different courage."
    "You breathe. Your chest feels compressed: decision is a physical thing now, not only a moral ledger. The group's faces line up—Nora tired, careful; Luca hot, immediate; Samir steady as tide; Ari cool, managerial. None of them is wrong. None of them is sufficient."
    "You glance at your notebook. The pen rests on a blank line. The rain throws itself at the windows like percussion, relentless. The music inside you—the drum of obligation, the high violin of fear, the low hum of strategy—coalesces into a single, very loud insistence: choose."
